<div id="review_1188480269" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1188480269" />
    <a title="It&#39;s Mini" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/38937675-it-s-mini"><img alt="It&#39;s Mini" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1588254165p2/38937675.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1188480269?book_show_action=true">Feb 02, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="It&#39;s Mini" class="user" itemprop="url" name="It&#39;s Mini" href="/user/show/38937675-it-s-mini">It&#39;s Mini</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780141439501" href="/book/show/12230.Pygmalion">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1188480269" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14097697020347849439"> I really don&apos;t know why Pygmalion is still called a romance. I mean, Shaw himself was very dissapointed at the fact that his socialistic drama became a success as a romance. Shaw wanted to liberate his play from the traditional conventions of a romance, that&apos;s why he reversed the romantic story by giving a different end, marking Eliza&apos;s emancipation and independence. If this was a typical love story, the two protagonists would have been married at the end. But Shaw implies that Mr. Higgings wil</span>
  <span id="freeText14097697020347849439" style="display:none"> I really don't know why Pygmalion is still called a romance. I mean, Shaw himself was very dissapointed at the fact that his socialistic drama became a success as a romance. Shaw wanted to liberate his play from the traditional conventions of a romance, that's why he reversed the romantic story by giving a different end, marking Eliza's emancipation and independence. If this was a typical love story, the two protagonists would have been married at the end. But Shaw implies that Mr. Higgings will never accept ELiza as an equal even though she becomes economical and emotional independent from him at the end of the play. He wanted to attack the idea of subordination of women by creating a play of social utility that may help people in his age rethink their values and manners towards what he thought to be the most exploited creature on earth, women.<br /> <br /> So maybe it's time for Goodreads to change the title "a romance" because it does not reflect neither Shaw's intentions nor the play's true nature. </span>
  <a data-text-id="14097697020347849439" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


